The '''Rijksmuseum''' is the Dutch national museum dedicated to arts and history, located in [[Amsterdam]]. Founded in 1800 in The Hague and moved to Amsterdam in 1808, it has occupied its current Pierre Cuypers-designed building since 1885.

The museum holds a collection of around one million objects from the years 1200 to 2000, including masterpieces by Rembrandt, [[Johannes Vermeer|Vermeer]], and Frans Hals, and is best known for "The Night Watch" and a comprehensive survey of Dutch Golden Age painting.
